snippet.title: Paris, France Walking Tour
snippet.description:
Take a 12 mile (19 km) walk through the streets of Paris and see the Louvre, Notre Dame, Champs-Élysées, Arc de Triomphe, the Eiffel Tower, and more. Click on a time link below to skip ahead to a specific location. 

▼▼Video Timeline Links▼▼
00:06 - The Louvre Museum
07:40 - Walk along the Seine River towards Notre Dame
19:52 - Notre Dame
25:00 - Wallk along the Seine River towards Arc de Triomphe
43:22 - Tuileries Garden
50:41 - Luxor Obelisk
53:47 - Avenue des Champs-Élysées 
1:10:40 - Arc De Triomphe
1:28:44 - The Eiffel Tower
1:41:00 - Champ de Mars Park
1:55:18 - The Army Museum/The National Residence of the Invalids
2:03:35 - Esplanade des Invalides
2:08:59 - Pont Alexandre III Bridge
2:13:17 - The Grand Palace
BEAUTIFUL PARIS STREETS
2:22:16 - Cour du Commerce-Saint-André
2:25:26 - Rue de Buci
2:27:43 - Rue des Rosiers & Rue Saint-Antoine
2:38:51 - Rue des Barres to Notre Dame

comments.textDisplay:
A great idea! Paris is definitely a "walking city". It should be mentioned that one of the things that makes walking around European cities in general, and Paris in particular, is that the buildings are all the same height, which gives the pedestrian a unified field of vision that is psychologically pleasing.

I would break the walk down into neighborhoods-3 hours is too long- pause and turn my head to admire some of the amazing architecture and shop windows displays. The center of Paris is full of magnificent "hôtels" or mansions and very cool boutiques. On one of my walks in the Marais I came upon the remnants of Phillippe Auguste's wall that surrounded medieval Paris in the 12th century.

replies.textDisplay: For about 30 years I lived across the border, about a 4 hour train/car ride from Paris, so I was there often. This was a great walk-around.  I love the view from the steps up above in the 18th Arrond. on Montmartre.. site of Painter's Square. All the famous nightspots like the Moulin Rouge sit just down below. Fantastic view of the city. I always try to wave hello to the two Statues of Liberty.... the one on her own little island in the Seine and the smaller one in the Luxembourg Gardens (an excellent, fairly-quiet spot in the city, another perfect spot to chill out and enjoy a picnic).

comments.textDisplay: How many countries have u visited in your life, and which one was or is your favorite and why?
comments.textOriginal: How many countries have u visited in your life, and which one was or is your favorite and why?

replies.textDisplay: USA, Canada, Mexico, Australia, Vietnam, Norway, France, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Croatia, Egypt, UK, and Italy.  I guess that makes 14. So I'm from the US and that tops my list. I've been to almost every state and I love road trips and the US is great to explore...but it's big. Where I grew up it was 2 hours to everything...mountains, ocean, big cities.  Italy is great to explore..and its small. :) After the US, Italy really is my favorite. I lived in Australia for a short while as a kid. I've lived in Italy now 4 years. I've only visited the rest. Within an hour of where I live now, there is so much to see and explore. It is always interesting. Southern Italy is just different enough from northern Italy and the rest of Western Europe to make me feel out of my comfort zone to an extent. It is grittier. When I got to Germany for example...it feels like a European Washington state..but with more castles.
